  "published": "2025-03-10",
  "runtimeMin": 78,
  "format": "Sean and Amanda dig into Bong Joon-ho's post-Parasite blank check, then rank all eight of his features.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "‘Mickey 17’",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Mickey 17",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Bong's $120M Warner Bros. follow-up to Parasite, from Edward Ashton's novel Mickey7. Robert Pattinson plays an 'expendable' who's killed and reprinted on an ice-world expedition run by a Trump-ish megachurch figure (Mark Ruffalo). Both hosts admire the craft and Pattinson's Keaton-esque physical work, but both think the tone (noir, slapstick, and broad political satire all at once) never settles. Sean calls it the second-best movie of the year so far."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "ranking",
      "heading": "The Bong Joon-ho Rankings",
      "note": "all eight features, best to worst",
      "subject": "Bong Joon-ho",
      "ranked": true,
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Parasite",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "No. 1, and it isn't close: the pair jokingly cut to 'Parasite 1, what goes 5, 4, 3.' The literalized basement-and-house metaphor, and its complicated, unhappy ending."
        },
        {
          "title": "Memories of Murder",
          "year": 2003,
          "note": "No. 2. His serial-killer film built on the unsolvability of life; traded influence with Fincher. Song Kang-ho is 'amazing.'"
        },
        {
          "title": "The Host",
          "year": 2006,
          "note": "No. 3, and Amanda's personal favorite: 'Mean Spielberg mode.' A straight creature movie that's really about government and family, with that formaldehyde-down-the-drain opening."
        },
        {
          "title": "Mother",
          "year": 2009,
          "note": "No. 4. Sean argues it has his best ending; the closest of the Korean films to Parasite in its grounded family-crime register."
        },
        {
          "title": "Snowpiercer",
          "year": 2013,
          "note": "No. 5. Praised as 'the most propulsive,' with the door-breaching push forward called 'cinema,' but graded an 8 against the top four's 9s and 10s. The Weinstein cut fight is recalled."
        },
        {
          "title": "Okja",
          "year": 2017,
          "note": "No. 6. Amanda defends it ('mean Spielberg,' the baby-pig ending wrecks her); Sean finds it broad and thematically redundant, his least-loved of the big films."
        },
        {
          "title": "Mickey 17",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "No. 7. Placed high in the pantheon of a director with no bad films, but the tonal spray keeps it at the bottom of the majors for both."
        },
        {
          "title": "Barking Dogs Never Bite",
          "year": 2000,
          "note": "Last. His debut comedy, 'a trial run': you can see the filmmaker forming, but neither returns to it."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
